📌 Java String Concatenation & Character Operations – Summary
String is a non-primitive data type (a class in Java).
The + operator has two purposes:
Arithmetic addition for numeric data types.
String concatenation when at least one operand is a String.
Java evaluates expressions from left to right.
Parentheses () have higher precedence and are evaluated first.
Once a String is encountered in an expression, subsequent + operations perform concatenation.
Numeric values appearing after a String are automatically converted to String.
char is a primitive data type that stores a single Unicode character.
Characters are internally represented by their numeric Unicode values (which match ASCII for standard English characters).
Arithmetic operations (+, -, etc.) on char use their numeric Unicode values.
Concatenating a char with a String results in String concatenation.
Performing arithmetic between two char values produces a numeric result, not another char.
Character literals can participate in arithmetic expressions just like numeric values.
ASCII/Unicode values of characters can be obtained using type casting or by adding 0.
Standard ASCII values (0–127) fall within the range of the byte data type.
Common ASCII ranges:
A–Z → 65–90
a–z → 97–122
0–9 → 48–57
Java performs automatic type conversion (type promotion) during mixed-type expressions.
Understanding the evaluation order is essential to correctly predict the output of expressions involving String, char, and numeric data types.